872/Child-abuse-case-dropped-against-Labour-peer-for-second-time.html |title=Child abuse case dropped against Labour peer for second time|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=16 April 2015|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n*21 April \u2013 following a six-week trial, Justin Robertson is jailed for life with a minimum tariff of thirty-two years for the September 2014 contract killing of Pennie Davis at the behest of her stepson. Benjamin Carr, who paid Robertson \u00a31,500 to carry out the killing, is convicted of conspiracy to murder and will serve at least thirty years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-32398463 |title=Life sentence for man guilty of Pennie Davis New Forest murder |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=21 April 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n*22 April \u2013 supermarket retailer [[Tesco]] posts a record \u00a36,400,000,000 annual loss for the year ending in February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-32408661 |title=Tesco posts record \u00a36.4bn annual loss |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=22 April 2015 |accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref>\n*26 April\n**More than 38,000 people take part in this year's [[2015 London Marathon|London Marathon]], making it the biggest in the event's thirty-five-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-32463424 |title=London Marathon: Thousands take part in biggest race |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=26 April 2015 |accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>\n**The government donates \u00a35,000,000 and humanitarian aid to help people affected by the recent [[April 2015 Nepal earthquake|earthquake]] in [[Nepal]], which killed over 6,000 people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32474414 |title=Nepal earthquake: UK government gives \u00a35m |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=26 April 2015 |accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>\n*27 April\n**The [[British Red Cross]] confirms that there are still dozens of Britons who have still not been traced following the earthquake in Nepal two days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32480795 |title=Nepal earthquake: Dozens of Britons yet to be traced |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=27 April 2015 |accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref>\n**Former [[Oxfordshire]] nurse Andrew Hutchinson is jailed for eighteen years for a [[rape]], [[sexual assault]] and [[voyeurism]] case involving unconscious women between 2011\u201313; two of which took place at the [[John Radcliffe Hospital]] in [[Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-32486188 |title=Nurse Andrew Hutchinson jailed for attacks on patients |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=27 April 2015 |accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref>\n*28 April \u2013 figures show that the rate of economic growth halved to 0.3% in the first quarter, marking the slowest quarterly growth in two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-32493745 |title=UK economic growth slows to 0.3% |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=28 April 2015 |accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n*29 April\n**The [[UK Supreme Court]] rules that the government must take immediate action to cut [[Air pollution in the United Kingdom|air pollution]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-32512152 |title=Court orders UK to cut NO2 air pollution |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=29 April 2015 |accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> following a case brought by lawyers at ClientEarth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clientearth.org/news/press-releases/uk-supreme-court-orders-government-to-take-immediate-action-on-air-pollution-2843|title=UK Supreme Court orders Government to take \"immediate action\" on air pollution|publisher=ClientEarth|date=29 April 2015|accessdate=29 April 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505041213/http://www.clientearth.org/news/press-releases/uk-supreme-court-orders-government-to-take-immediate-action-on-air-pollution-2843|archivedate=5 May 2015}}</ref>\n**Eighteen-year-old Kazi Islam, who was inspired by the [[murder of Lee Rigby]], is convicted by a jury at the Old Bailey of grooming a vulnerable friend to kill two soldiers, and buying ingredients for a [[pipe bomb]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32521780 |title=Teenager Kazi Islam found guilty of terror grooming |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=29 April 2015 |accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n**The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] confirms that a Briton living overseas was among the 6,000 victims killed in the Nepal earthquake, and it is feared that another British national has been killed at the [[Everest Base Camp]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32513534|title=British death in Nepal earthquake confirmed|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=29 April 2015|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n**A blaze causes extensive damage at [[Clandon Park]], a stately home in Surrey.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-32524445|title=Clandon Park House in Surrey hit by major fire|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=29 April 2015|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n*30 April \u2013 the three main political party leaders, David Cameron, Ed Miliband and Nick Clegg, take part in the final televised debate before the general election on a special edition of ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32533048|title=Leaders grilled by audience in Question Time special|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n*2 May \u2013 [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]] gives birth to a daughter at [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]] in [[London]] who becomes fourth in line to the throne and [[Queen Elizabeth II]]'s fifth great-grandchild.<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Davies |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ratcliffe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/may/02/duchess-of-cambridge-gives-birth-to-baby-girl-prince-william |title=Royal baby: Duchess of Cambridge gives birth to baby girl |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 May 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> She is subsequently named [[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge|Charlotte Elizabeth Diana]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32583432 |title=Royal princess named Charlotte Elizabeth Diana |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref>\n*7 May\n**The [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] takes place, resulting in the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] winning an outright majority with 331 seats, and securing [[David Cameron]] a [[Second Cameron ministry|second term in office]]. Meanwhile, in Scotland, a huge surge to the [[Scottish National Party]] sees the party win fifty-six of the fifty-nine Scottish seats available, an increase of fifty seats compared to their 2010 total. The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] wins 232 seats across the UK, with modest gains in England more than offset by heavy losses in Scotland, while the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] are almost wiped out with just eight of their previous fifty-seven seats remaining.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32659720 |title=UK election results: David Cameron pledges a 'greater Britain' |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-scotland-32668247 |title=Election 2015: Sturgeon says Scotland 'voted for change' |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n**[[2015 United Kingdom local elections|Local elections]] also take place in 279 councils across England, with the Conservatives gaining 25 councils to control 130 overall, the Labour Party lose four seats, leaving them with 67 councils, while the Liberal Democrats lose four to control three councils.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2015/results/councils |title=England council results |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n*8 May\n**Commemorations are held to celebrate the seventieth anniversary of [[VE Day]], the end of [[World War II]] on the continent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32626551 |title=VE Day 70th anniversary marked with events across Europe |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n**[[Ed Miliband]], [[Nick Clegg]] and [[Nigel Farage]], the three respective leaders of Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the [[UK Independence Party]], all announce their resignations in the wake of their electoral defeats.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-32633388 |title=Labour election results: Ed Miliband resigns as leader |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32667695 |title=Election results: Nick Clegg resigns as Leader of the Liberal Democrats after their worst electoral defeat, seeing them no longer the UK's third party. |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32654046 |title=Nigel Farage resigns as UKIP leader |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> Farage's resignation is subsequently rejected after \"overwhelming evidence\" that members of his party disagreed with his decision to quit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-32696505 |title=Farage stays as UKIP leader after resignation rejected |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=11 May 2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n*13 May \u2013 figures show that unemployment fell to 1,830,000 in the first quarter, a 35,000 decrease from the last quarter, and the lowest figure in seven years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-32719779 |title=UK unemployment falls to seven-year low |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=13 May 2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n*15 May \u2013 the [[Rail, Maritime and Transport workers union]] (RMT) announce that Network Rail workers will stage a 24-hour strike from 5.00pm on 25 May over pay and conditions, the first national rail strike in the UK for two decades.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32748029 |title=Rail workers to strike on bank holiday Monday |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=15 May 2015 |accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> The strike is called off on 21 May after a pay deal is reached with Network Rail management.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32832191 |title=Rail unions call off national bank holiday strike |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=21 May 2015 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n*16 May \u2013 the [[Church of Scotland]] votes to allow the ordination of gay ministers in [[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnerships]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-32760416 |title=Church of Scotland votes to allow gay ministers in civil partnerships |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=16 May 2015 |accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n*19 May\n**[[Charles, Prince of Wales]] begins his official four-day tour of the Republic of Ireland having a controversial meeting with [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] leader [[Gerry Adams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-32786393 |title=Prince Charles meets Sinn F\u00e9in leader Gerry Adams |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n**Figures show that the main measure of [[inflation]] turned negative in April for the first time on record, falling to \u22120.1%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-32793481 |title=UK inflation rate turns negative |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n**Nine men are arrested,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-32799703 |title=Hatton Garden raid: Nine men arrested |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref> and eight charged the following day,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-32822298 |title=Hatton Garden raid: Eight men charged over burglary heist |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=20 May 2015 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref> in connection with the [[Hatton Garden safe deposit burglary|Hatton Garden safe deposit raid]] in early April.\n*21 May \u2013 cashless payments now exceed the use of notes and coins, with cash volumes expected to fall by 30% over the next ten years, according to the [[Payments Council]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-32778196 |title=Cashless payments overtake the use of notes and coins |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=21 May 2015 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n*22 May \u2013 an earthquake of magnitude 4.2 is felt across East [[Kent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-32840579|title=Kent earthquake causes homes to shake|publisher=[[BBC]] |date=22 May 2015 |accessdate=23 May 2015}}</ref>\n*28 May \u2013 the RMT calls two national strikes for June after failing to reach a deal with Network Rail management. A 24-hour strike will begin at 5.00pm on 4 June, and a 48-hour strike will take place from 5.00pm on 9 June.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32920794 |title=Network Rail workers to go on strike in June |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=28 May 2015 |accessdate=28 May 2015}}</ref> The strikes are suspended on 1 June, after a 2% salary increase offer from Network Rail.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32956876 |title=UK rail strikes suspended after 2% pay rise offer |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=1 June 2015 |accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n*30 May \u2013 in football, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] win the [[2015 FA Cup Final]] defeating [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 4\u20130 at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]].\n\n===June===\n*1 June\n**National rail strikes planned for 4 and 9 June are called off after a pay deal is reached.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/story/2015-06-01/acas-network-rail-strikes-called-off/ |title=ACAS \u2013 Network rail strikes called off |work=[[ITV News]] |date=1 June 2015 |accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> \n**[[Charles Kennedy]], former leader of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], dies, aged fifty-five in [[Fort William, Highland]], of haemorrhage linked to alcoholism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-32970337|title=Tributes paid to Charles Kennedy|date=2 June 2015|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n*2 June \u2013 a serious collision on [[The Smiler (roller coaster)|The Smiler]] ride at [[Alton Towers]] causes four people to be airlifted to hospital due to their injuries. The incident is one of the biggest accidents ever to occur at Alton Towers, and the park is closed for several days pending investigations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32980354 |title=Alton Towers Smiler crash: Four seriously hurt |work=BBC News|date=2 June 2015|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n*6 June \u2013 [[Golden Horn (horse)|Golden Horn]], ridden by [[Frankie Dettori]], wins the [[2015 Epsom Derby]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Keogh|first1=Frank|title=Frankie Dettori wins Epsom Derby on favourite Golden Horn|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/horse-racing/33036202|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n*9 June \u2013 [[HSBC]], the world's largest banking retailer, announce plans to cut 25,000 jobs worldwide, including 8,000 in the UK. It also plans to close some of its UK branches, and rename the HSBC brand in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-33058957 |title=HSBC plans to cut 8,000 jobs in the UK in savings drive |work=BBC News|date=9 June 2015 |accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n*10 June\n**Chancellor George Osborne announces government plans to sell off its stake in the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-33088599 |title=RBS government stake to be sold, chancellor announces |work=BBC News|date=11 June 2015 |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n**A nationwide poll to find a [[national bird]] for the UK has chosen the [[European robin|robin]] as the public's favourite candidate.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jack |last=Hardy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/robin-crowned-as-britains-national-bird-after-200000strong-ballot-10311482.html |title=Robin crowned as Britain's national bird after 200,000-strong ballot |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=10 June 2015 |accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref>\n*11 June \u2013 a youth is detained by police after a teacher is stabbed in front of students at a school in Bradford.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bradford-west-yorkshire-33100114|title=Boy arrested after Bradford teacher stabbing|work=BBC News|date=11 June 2015 |accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n*13 June \u2013 Trooping the Colour takes place in London marking the Queen's official birthday. It is the Duchess of Cambridge's first appearance since the birth of Princess Charlotte. Prince George also makes his first appearance on the balcony of Buckingham Palace.\n*14 June \u2013 a statue of [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] is unveiled by Speaker [[John Bercow]] at [[Runnymede]] in Surrey ahead of the Magna Carta celebrations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2015-06-14/statue-of-the-queen-unveiled-to-mark-magna-carta-milestone/|title=Statue of the Queen unveiled to mark Magna Carta milestone|work=ITV News|publisher=ITV|date=14 June 2015 |accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n*15 June \u2013 the [[British Royal Family|royal family]], the [[David Cameron|Prime Minister]], the [[Justin Welby|Archbishop of Canterbury]] and other dignitaries attend a ceremony at Runnymede to mark the eight-hundredth anniversary of the [[Magna Carta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33126723|title=Magna Carta 'changed the world', David Cameron tells at anniversary event|work=BBC News|date=15 June 2015 |accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33131092|title=Queen attends 800th anniversary ceremony|work=BBC News|date=15 June 2015 |accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n*18 June \u2013 a government report reveals that the [[Palace of Westminster]] is in need of repair, and recommends that MPs leave the building for two years in order for the repairs to be carried out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/768c237e-15af-11e5-8e6a-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3dyBE8rB7|title=MPs face House of Commons move while palace is repaired|work=Financial Times|date=19 June 2015|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref>\n*20 June \u2013 some 250,000 people take to the streets in cities such as London, Bristol and Manchester in a demonstration backed by the [[Anti-austerity movement in the United Kingdom|People's Assembly Against Austerity]] to protest against the UK Government's austerity programme.\n*24 June \u2013 it is announced that [[Buckingham Palace]] is in need of repair and the Royal Household debates whether the Queen should move to Windsor Castle.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33250274|title=Queen could move out of Buckingham Palace|work=BBC News|date=24 June 2015 |accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref>\n*25 June \u2013 the [[UK population]] has grown by almost 500,000 to reach 64,596,800 in 2014 \u2013 an above average increase compared with increases over the last decade \u2013 according to the [[Office for National Statistics]] (ONS). The percentage of older people continues to increase, and the median age is now forty years, the highest ever recorded.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33266792|title=UK population increases by 500,000, official figures show|work=BBC News|date=25 June 2015 |accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n*26 June \u2013 at least thirty Britons are among 37 people believed to be dead after a [[2015 Sousse attacks|terrorist attack on a beach]] near the [[Tunisia]]n resort town of [[Sousse]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/jun/26/tunisia-beach-resort-attack-multiple-deaths-live-updates|title=Terror attacks: separate attacks in Tunisia, France and Kuwait leave more than 60 dead|work=The Guardian|date=26 June 2015 |accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33299523|title=British Tunisia death toll rises to 15|work=BBC News|date=27 June 2015 |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1509937/memorial-on-beach-after-30-britons-killed |title=Memorial On Beach After 30 Britons Killed |publisher=British Sky Broadcasting |work=Sky News |date=30 June 2015 |accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n*28 June\n**The [[14th Dalai Lama]] makes an appearance at the [[Glastonbury Festival 2015|2015 Glastonbury Festival]], praising the event as \"a festival of people, not governments or politicians\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Ian |last=Young |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-33303900 |title=Glastonbury: Dalai Lama warms up for Lionel Richie |work=BBC News|date=28 June 2015 |accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n**A coach driver from Northern Ireland is killed, and several teachers and schoolchildren from [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]] in Essex are injured, after a coach crashes near [[Ostend]] in Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33303121|title=NI driver killed in Belgium school trip bus crash|work=BBC News|date=28 June 2015 |accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n*29 June\n**A major planning application by energy firm [[Cuadrilla Resources|Cuadrilla]] to begin [[fracking]] in [[Lancashire]] is rejected by the local council.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lancashire-33313084|title=Council blocks Little Plumpton fracking application|work=BBC News|date=29 June 2015 |accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref>\n**Production ceases at the last deep coal mine in the [[South Yorkshire Coalfield]], [[Hatfield Colliery]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/28622652/hatfield-colliery-closure-speeds-up-uk-exit-from-deep-coal-mining/|title=Hatfield Colliery closure speeds up UK exit from deep coal mining|publisher=Reuters|location=London|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=19 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723164012/https://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/28622652/hatfield-colliery-closure-speeds-up-uk-exit-from-deep-coal-mining/|archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref>\n*30 June \u2013 police officers, intelligence officials, soldiers and emergency services take part in a [[counter-terrorism]] exercise, codenamed Strong Tower, in London. The terror attack simulation has been six months in the planning and is the country's largest such exercise to date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33315691|title=Major counter-terrorism exercise in London|work=BBC News|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*1 July \u2013 a level three \"[[heatwave]] action\" heat-health alert is declared by the [[Met Office]], as a temperature of 36.7&nbsp;\u00b0C is recorded at [[Heathrow]] in London; the hottest UK temperature in twelve years, and the hottest July day on record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-33324881|title=Hottest July day ever recorded in England|publisher=[[BBC ]]|work=[[BBC News]]|date=1 July 2015|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n*3 July\n**Across the UK, a one-minute silence is held at midday to remember the 38 victims \u2013 including 30 British people \u2013 who died in the Tunisia beach attack a week earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33382486|title=Tunisia attack: Minute's silence held for victims|work=BBC News|date=3 July 2015|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n**Production is suspended at the last substantial coal mine in Wales, [[Aberpergwm]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/jobs-coal-mothballed/story-26768464-detail/story.html|title=Jobs to go as South West Wales coal mine is mothballed|work=[[South Wales Evening Post]]|date=2015-06-26|accessdate=2016-08-20}}</ref>\n*4 July \u2013 [[England women's national football team|England]] finish third in the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 Women's World Cup]] after defeating [[Germany women's national football team|Germany]] 1\u20130 in the third place play-off.<ref>{{cite news|last=Magowan|first=Alistair|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33085963|work=BBC Sport|title=Women's World Cup: Germany Women 0\u20131 England Women|publisher=BBC|date=4 July 2015|accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n*5 July\n**[[Lewis Hamilton]] wins the [[2015 British Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Benson |first=Andrew |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/33401990 |work=BBC Sport |title=Lewis Hamilton wins British GP brilliantly after late rain |publisher=BBC |date=5 July 2015 |accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n**[[UNESCO]] gives the [[Forth Bridge]] the status of a [[List of World Heritage Sites in the United Kingdom|World Heritage Site]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-33397980|title=Forth Bridge given World Heritage Site status|work=BBC News|date=5 July 2015|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref>\n** Christening of HRH Princess Charlotte of Cambridge at the St. Mary Magdalene Church on the Sandringham House Estate in Norfolk. Among the godparents is Lady Sarah Fellowes, a niece of Diana, Princess of Wales\n*6 July \u2013 a major incident is declared by [[Sussex Police]] after two people are left with life-threatening injuries as two double-decker buses collide on North Street, [[Brighton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-33406558 |title=Two buses crash in Brighton city centre |work=BBC News |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref>\n*7 July \u2013 the UK marks the tenth anniversary of the [[7/7 attacks]] with memorial services and one minute's silence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33407554 |title=7 July London bombings: Ceremonies in memory of victims |work=BBC News |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n*8 July \u2013 as part of his first Conservative [[Budget]], the Chancellor [[George Osborne]] unveils billions in welfare cuts, but also announces a [[National Living Wage]] of \u00a39 an hour by 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-33437115 |title=Budget 2015: Osborne unveils National Living Wage |work=BBC News |date=8 July 2015 |accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n*9 July \u2013 tube and train strikes cause travel chaos in and around London, with the entire [[London Underground]] network shut down and many rail services cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-33456830 |title=Tube and train strikes: Commuters face travel disruption |work=BBC News |date=9 July 2015 |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n*10 July\n**Production ceases at the last deep coal mine in [[Nottinghamshire]], [[Thoresby Colliery]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-33409746|title=Nottinghamshire's Thoresby Colliery closes after 90 years|work=BBC News|date=10 July 2015|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Thousands of British holidaymakers begin to return home from [[Tunisia]] after a warning from the [[Foreign Office]] that another terror attack is \"highly likely\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33473433 |title=Tunisia travel alert: Thousands of Britons fly home |work=BBC News |date=10 July 2015 |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref>\n*13 July \u2013 hundreds of flights are disrupted at [[London Heathrow Airport|Heathrow Airport]] in London after members of the climate change protest group [[Plane Stupid]] break through the metal fence, get onto the northern runway, and chain themselves together in protest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-33503167|title=Heathrow Airport climate change protest delays flights|work=BBC News |date=13 July 2015 |accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref>\n*16 July \u2013 [[Tim Farron]] is elected as the new leader of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].<ref>{{cite web| date=16 July 2015|publisher=Liberal Democrats| title=Tim Farron elected as Leader of the Liberal Democrats| accessdate=23 September 2015| url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/tim-farron-elected-leader-liberal-democrats}}</ref>\n*17 July\n**The first [[female genital mutilation]] protection order in the UK is obtained by [[Bedfordshire Police]], preventing two young girls thought to be at risk from travelling to [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33572428 |title=UK's first FGM protection order secured by Beds police |work=BBC News |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> \n**Four people are thought to be trapped and four others are taken to hospital, after three explosions at a wood treatment works in [[Bosley]] near [[Macclesfield]] in Cheshire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-33566064 |title=Bosley explosion: 'Four missing' in Wood Flour Mills blast |work=BBC News |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n*20 July \u2013 in golf, [[Zach Johnson]] of the USA wins the [[2015 Open Championship]], the 144th edition of the tournament, at [[Old Course at St Andrews|St Andrews]], Fife, defeating South Africa's [[Louis Oosthuizen]] and [[Marc Leishman]] of Australia in a playoff.\n*21 July \u2013 Chancellor George Osborne launches a spending review that calls for \u00a320,000,000,000 of cuts to Whitehall budgets. Each unprotected department is asked to create savings plans of be